description.narrative:
The IUCN global results framework shows results on a very aggregated level as this is an organisation with 1.300 governmental and NGO members, comparable with an UN organisation in size, complexity and scope, and aiming for global impact. As described elsewhere, there are three independent programme areas. Each have their own global result defined:
1. Valuing and conserving nature - &quot;The risk facing species and ecosystems is reduced&quot;
2. Promoting and supporting effective and equitable governance of natural resources - &quot;Natural resource governance at all levels enables ... effective conservation and equitable social outcomes....&quot;
3. Deploying nature-based solutions to address societal changes including climate change, food security and economic and social development - &quot;Societies recognise and enhance the ability of healthy and restored ecosystems....&quot;
Below these, each area has three outcome obejctives or &quot;sub-results&quot; defined. For instance, a sub-result under (2.) on natural resource governance is &quot;Governance at national and subnational levels related to nature and natural resources is strengthened through the application of the rights-based approach, and incorporation of good governance principles&quot;. The sub-result is specified into three targets and a number of &quot;component programme contributions&quot; - some of the latter (not all) are directly attributable to the work of IUCN and could be considered as something between outcome objectives and outputs. Example: &quot;Water management enabled in 8 BRIDGE basins + local water governance in 3 basins in Africa&quot; and &quot;rights-based approach enabled in 1 SUSTAIN growth corridor&quot;.
As mentioned above, the results framework is also linked to the Sustainable Development Goals (1, 2, 5, 6, 11, 13,14, 15, 16, 17).
Also mentioned above: the proposed results and indicators will be validated by IUCN during 2017. Sida recognizes the size of the challenge and understands that the results framework should still be considered &quot;work in progress&quot;. As such it should remain an issue for follow-up from Sida during the program period.
Since there will be a soft earmarking for marine Plastics and Coastal Communities separate reporting will be provided by IUCN. It is expected that results will be focussed on the following: 1) Understanding the state and impact of plastic pollution in the Indian Ocean and Asia Pacific regions 2) Local and regional capacity building to facilitate national action to control plastic pollution in the Indian Ocean and Asia Pacific 3) Supporting national and regional policy frameworks and legislative reform processes to address plastics in the Indian Ocean and Asia Pacific regions 4) Engaging and mobilising business actors in support of effective management and reduction of plastic pollution
